ing provides a valuable history of public health in Los Angeles, living conditions among Mexican immigrants, and the ways in which regional racial categories influence national laws and practices. Molina’s compelling study advances our understanding of the complexity of racial politics, attesting that racism is not static and that different groups can occupy different places in the racial order at different times.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAsian AmericansxHealth and hygienexHistoryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aAsian AmericansxHealth and hygienezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxHealth and hygienexHistoryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aImmigrantsxHealth and hygienezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aMexican AmericansxHealth and hygienexHistoryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aMexican AmericansxHealth and hygienezCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aPublic healthxHistoryxCaliforniaxLos Angeles. 0aPublic healthzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aafrican americans.  aamerica.  aamerican citizens.  aasian americans.  achinese immigrants.  acultural history.  aearly 20th century.  aethnic studies.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  ahealth officials.  ajapanese immigrants.  alabor exploitation.  alegal exclusion.  aliving conditions.  alos angeles.  amexican americans.  amexican immigrants.  anonfiction.  apublic health.  arace and law.  arace issues.  aracial groups.  aracial politics.  aracialization.  aracism.  ascientific developments.  aunited states.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093920240uhttps://www.deg